    {
      "id": "334272136",
      "type": "complexNotes",
      "links": {
        "self": "https://secure.simplepractice.com/frontend/complex-notes/334272136"
      },
      "attributes": {
        "templateQuestions": "[{\"id\":1,\"questionType\":\"FREE_TEXT\",\"question\":\"Subjective\",\"formattedQuestion\":null,\"inGroup\":false,\"intakeAnswers\":[],\"required\":false},{\"id\":2,\"questionType\":\"FREE_TEXT\",\"question\":\"Objective\",\"formattedQuestion\":null,\"inGroup\":false,\"intakeAnswers\":[],\"required\":false},{\"id\":3,\"questionType\":\"FREE_TEXT\",\"question\":\"Assessment\",\"formattedQuestion\":null,\"inGroup\":false,\"intakeAnswers\":[],\"required\":false},{\"id\":4,\"questionType\":\"FREE_TEXT\",\"question\":\"Plan\",\"formattedQuestion\":null,\"inGroup\":false,\"intakeAnswers\":[],\"required\":false}]",
        "userAnswers": "[{\"questionId\":1,\"questionType\":\"FREE_TEXT\",\"freeTextAnswer\":\"Subjective\\n\\nJamie D. Appleseed, a 30-year-old adult, presented for the initial therapy session. Client reported significant ongoing anxiety with daily panic attacks, describing palpitations, shortness of breath, and a pervasive sense of impending doom. Jamie noted that their alcohol consumption has escalated markedly over the past six months in response to work-related stress following a management change. The client is consuming 6 to 8 beers per day and reports mild morning tremors and nausea on days when alcohol intake is reduced. Jamie expressed a strong desire to change but voiced uncertainty about tolerating anxiety without the use of alcohol. The client denied suicidal ideation, homicidal ideation, or intent to harm self or others.\",\"formattedFreeTextAnswer\":\"<p>Subjective</p>\\n\\n<p>Jamie D. Appleseed, a 30-year-old adult, presented for the initial therapy session. Client reported significant ongoing anxiety with daily panic attacks, describing palpitations, shortness of breath, and a pervasive sense of impending doom. Jamie noted that their alcohol consumption has escalated markedly over the past six months in response to work-related stress following a management change. The client is consuming 6 to 8 beers per day and reports mild morning tremors and nausea on days when alcohol intake is reduced. Jamie expressed a strong desire to change but voiced uncertainty about tolerating anxiety without the use of alcohol. The client denied suicidal ideation, homicidal ideation, or intent to harm self or others.</p>\\n\"},{\"questionId\":2,\"questionType\":\"FREE_TEXT\",\"freeTextAnswer\":\"Objective\\n\\nClient appeared alert and oriented x3. Affect was anxious, mood was dysphoric but engaged. Speech was clear and goal-directed. Insight into the connection between anxiety and alcohol use was fair to good. Judgment appeared intact. No evidence of acute psychosis or dissociation. Vitals not assessed in outpatient setting.\",\"formattedFreeTextAnswer\":\"<p>Objective</p>\\n\\n<p>Client appeared alert and oriented x3. Affect was anxious, mood was dysphoric but engaged. Speech was clear and goal-directed. Insight into the connection between anxiety and alcohol use was fair to good. Judgment appeared intact. No evidence of acute psychosis or dissociation. Vitals not assessed in outpatient setting.</p>\\n\"},{\"questionId\":3,\"questionType\":\"FREE_TEXT\",\"freeTextAnswer\":\"Assessment\\n\\nJamie presents with co-occurring Generalized Anxiety Disorder (GAD) and Alcohol Use Disorder (AUD) of moderate severity. The two conditions appear mutually reinforcing: anxiety drives alcohol use, while alcohol use disrupts neurobiological regulation and exacerbates rebound anxiety. The client’s mild withdrawal symptoms (tremors, nausea) suggest physiological dependence and require monitoring. Based on ASAM criteria, the client may meet criteria for Intensive Outpatient Program (IOP, Level 2.1) given withdrawal risk, functional impairment, and coping deficits. Strengths include internal motivation for change and a (currently strained) supportive partner relationship.\",\"formattedFreeTextAnswer\":\"<p>Assessment</p>\\n\\n<p>Jamie presents with co-occurring Generalized Anxiety Disorder (GAD) and Alcohol Use Disorder (AUD) of moderate severity. The two conditions appear mutually reinforcing: anxiety drives alcohol use, while alcohol use disrupts neurobiological regulation and exacerbates rebound anxiety. The client’s mild withdrawal symptoms (tremors, nausea) suggest physiological dependence and require monitoring. Based on ASAM criteria, the client may meet criteria for Intensive Outpatient Program (IOP, Level 2.1) given withdrawal risk, functional impairment, and coping deficits. Strengths include internal motivation for change and a (currently strained) supportive partner relationship.</p>\\n\"},{\"questionId\":4,\"questionType\":\"FREE_TEXT\",\"freeTextAnswer\":\"Plan\\n\\nEstablish therapeutic alliance and complete comprehensive intake documentation. Provide psychoeducation on the anxiety-AUD cycle. Screen for severity of withdrawal using standardized tools at next visit. Introduce distress tolerance and anxiety management skills (diaphragmatic breathing, grounding). Initiate referral discussion for IOP evaluation (ASAM Level 2.1). Coordinate with prescribing provider if pharmacological support for withdrawal or anxiety is indicated. Schedule follow-up session for 05/05/2026.\",\"formattedFreeTextAnswer\":\"<p>Plan</p>\\n\\n<p>Establish therapeutic alliance and complete comprehensive intake documentation. Provide psychoeducation on the anxiety-AUD cycle. Screen for severity of withdrawal using standardized tools at next visit. Introduce distress tolerance and anxiety management skills (diaphragmatic breathing, grounding). Initiate referral discussion for IOP evaluation (ASAM Level 2.1). Coordinate with prescribing provider if pharmacological support for withdrawal or anxiety is indicated. Schedule follow-up session for 05/05/2026.</p>\\n\"}]"
      },
